column1: Before 1 November 2022, will an executive order be signed or federal legislation become law that would forgive $10,000 or more in principal on federal student loan debts for at least ten million student loan borrowers?
column6: ['Finance', 'US Politics', 'US Policy']
Updating for passage of time. As cited by @sdesirae this could still happen, but later in the year past the deadline we're forecasting.

It might happen still but at this point, it wouldn’t happen before November 1st. It says in an article by AS, “According to the Department of Education the application period will be short and the deadline for the application is 31 December 2023, giving student plenty of time to access it.” This means that they still have time and that it would take around 6 more weeks at most from October to be processed.
While there is a chance the 8th circuit court lifts its hold before the end of tomorrow, I think this is unlikely
A court has frozen this statute but it is very likely that this order will go into effect due to public popularity and we will see high support for it.
I think just because of how soon that date is and because it hasn't happened yet that there is no chance that it will happen now.
The current Biden Student Loan forgiveness plan has been blocked by a federal appeals court, and even Biden himself has predicted that loans won't be forgiven until at least 2 weeks.
Hasn't happened yet.
Website to sign up going forward with Secretary of Education, but have not seen EO or legislation. Keep probability low.
happened

"A federal appeals court on Friday evening blocked the imminent cancellation of federal student loans under President Biden’s debt relief program, days after millions of borrowers began applying." —The Washington Post, 21 October 2022
This is hot button for Republicans sound box. Biden probably being discouraged to implement until after election. He got bang with Democrats with the promise. Also, the courts will slow it down.

The biggest motivator for President Biden signing his executive order would be to galvanize voters before mid-terms end. College educated individuals make up a large portion of the Democratic base and it is imperative that the Democrats can turn out this demographic for the upcoming elections. However, it could have the perverse cost of alienating moderate voters, and in swing states it could, moderates could make break the Democrats majority in Congress. The only reason I think Biden announced student debt relief in August was due to the fact that his approval ratings were dipping and this was a fairly simple way to try and boost polls amongst voters.
I forgot to update this. There won't be legislation, and the White House has gone forward without an executive order, so I assess these odds as quite remote.

I don't see this happening in the short term. However, there is an election upcoming and elections can change actions in unpredictable ways. I feel though that this is not a greatly popular issue among voters, thus pursuing it could be harmful politically.
hasn't happened yet
Doesn't seem likely. Biden hasn't talked about it for quite some time now.
Biden hasn't talked about this recently
Doesn't seem like its going anywhere
It hasn't happened yet. It does not seem to be a priority of the administration right now. The other debt forgiveness policy is going through the courts right now.
Throwing in the towel on my previous view of almost near certainty.
As of now, no EO or legislation has been passed, and loan repayment is still paused until December 21, 2022, so it is not likelyEO/Legislation will pass by November 1, 2022.

A little frustrated with GJ's ruling on this question. This policy accomplishes the same effect as a signed EO - the difference is a technicality, highlighting which runs counter to the spirit of good forecasting. But ... so be it.
Moved down the probability for federal legislation, but still in middle range for EO.

Balancing 4 months of being wrong with the hope that I'm right with the other 4. The only event that I see as a possibility is an EO, but that is unlikely as the current path through the DOE should prove lawful.

President Biden Administration likely try to sign EO into law to try to sway younger voters after losing many on economy, crime wave, and parent rights within school. Many from party are turning from administration, but this is one item that administration as a whole can stand behind though many think it does not go far enough. The delays in repay have gone over well and no one from either side have actively complained. President Biden will need to sign EO to make it happen though it can be overturned if not made into legislation. While he has the House and Senate he needs to push it through or it can be overturned. Though it would be messing just like other EO that effective widely never can really be overturned fully.
Lawsuits against this are unlikely to propel an Executive order because the best route to loan forgiveness is through the Department of Education that has broad authority to make new regulations.
I still think there will be some form of action necessary to double-prove DoE's authority to forego such an amount of taxpayer (Fed-printed/Chinese-borrowed,...) money, and legitimacy of plans.

Missed the part where the EdDept could do it on their own without an executive order. Legislation was a non-starter all along. An executive order is a specific sort of instrument, so it looks like The Aged Incumbent's minions will do this and his involvement will be limited to congratulating himself. He's had lots of practice at that; been incomparably good at it, at least since the New Castle City Council days in the 1970s (before you were born--remember, kids?).
Seems like Biden made the announcement without the accompanying executive order, and pushing a bill through Congress to get this done seems unlikely especially given the time frame of this question.
Seems like it's not going to be an executive order
Moving up my confidence level on this:

Looks like it's happening or already has. It is a pretty dumb idea even with the announced relatively mild targeting, since it seems to be a one-off unaccompanied by any component that might help reduce the preposterously high costs of postsecondary education and with no apparent provision for future students. Frankly, this is the sort of action that Third-World governments love to take in election years--splashy headlines at the announcement followed by glacial implementation, then eventually dying not with a bang but with a whimper.
I now see it's all through the Department of Education..
Seems this has been decided on already.

Okay, I get it now. This may not necessarily come via an executive order nor through legislation but rather through rules put forth by the Department of Education: https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/08/24/fact-sheet-president-biden-announces-student-loan-relief-for-borrowers-who-need-it-most/

"Still, The White House is currently under intense pressure to cancel student debt for all borrowers, and President Joe Biden has promised to make a decision on how to act, if at all, by the end of the month."
It definitely seems like the Biden administration is moving towards forgiving some student loans. What still makes me hesitant to push my forecast higher are the following:
This is repeatedly discussed and seems politically necessary at this point. Timing likely to be late October to be fresh for midterms. Maybe 10/25.

Dark Brandon is dragging his heels at least a little bit - it is surprising that they have not formally announced a debt pause yet given payments restart in like 20 days. Going to start reducing this as time passes, especially if there is no forgiveness by end of month

Changing my mind. This would be in fact a controversial measure, not likely to bring large political benefits. Now that Biden got his latest bill, the political need for student loan forgiveness is reduced. Most likely, the administration will just extend the moratorium on student loan payments, which expires on August 31 I think. The only argument for forgiveness is to fulfill an election promise, which could still happen after Nov 1.
Biden ain't got the balls
Praying an above average Brier score will help offset my bad mood when this goes through

Maybe slightly higher as some other challenges to the administration seem to be abating (inflation, etc.). However, I still see this as highly unlikely.

No apparent movement or discussion. And the only development is a much more modest proposal to offset interest accumulation: https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2022/07/09/biden-student-loans-interest-capitalization-limits/
No movement this week, and ... inflation. https://www.nytimes.com/2022/06/22/us/politics/biden-student-debt-inflation.html
Time decay back towards maybe.
Biden delaying an announcement until late summer. Either because he's discovered he hasn't the legal standing to do this or he wants to make an election season impact on younger voters.

"The Federal Reserve’s analysis found forgiving $10,000 per borrower would result in roughly 11.8 million borrowers – slightly more than 31% – having their entire balance eliminated. If the Biden administration were to move forward under this plan, an estimated $321 billion in federal student loans would be forgiven."
I'm mostly just tracking prediction markets on this one
- Biden forgave some debts https://www.politico.com/news/2022/06/01/biden-administration-student-loan-debt-00036572

This has been talked about for a while without seeming to gain traction. Democrats are still divided, not only on how much, but even if. Additionally, a highly inflationary economy seems like the least likely time to enact student loan forgiveness due to the impact on demand.
More noise in the press + prediction markets

If not for the tragedy in Uvalde, it seems that the policy would have been announced this weekend, according to the Washington Post. [1] The article says the White House estimates that 33% of the 41 million student loan borrowers would be potentially covered and that adding in the income limits would still leave 97% of that cohort eligible. By my calculations that would be about 13 million borrowers receiving $10,000 in relief.
Will be a political move to try to help in midterm elections
With Biden's approval rating down, I wouldn't see it out of question that such a thing occurs.

10K is likely the smallest amount the Biden administration could give to get some bump from the electorate. the small 10-30 K amount may also be chosen to not alienate those who are not currently in debt. Some offering will likely be down before the midterms, more than 10K seems to be the easier number, this could be a harder question. Now watch that I am wrong :)

$10K per borrower seems like the minimum he will do (and I believe what he pledged as a candidate). It will be smart politically before the midterms (to at least some demographics). Difficult to see him doing less than this, and the question only applies to 10M borrowers (there are 43M total).

I think the crowd median is at a good place (around 40 to 45%) but will remain slightly more optimistic due to possible political motives to at least get an executive order done before the Republicans can get a possible stronghold in Congress. Previously, Biden had a legal team go over the legality of signing an executive order but it seems there hasn't been un updated word on this matter. To me, Biden bringing this up again could signal that they haven't ruled out that executive orders pertaining to this issue is not illegal, per se. So will have to watch.
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/14/opinion/student-debt-cancel.htmlTimes comes out against it.
democrats don't have the votes

Reducing probability today. I am wondering if the wording of the question itself makes the outcome slightly less likely. I have been reading that many (even proponents) are hesitant to forgive an arbitrary, fixed amount. If a percentage is forgiven or interest eliminated etc., would this qualify as 10k forgiveness across the board? That being said, many articles describe how Biden does seem to be grappling with what flat amount of forgives would be appropriate…so may ultimately be a set amount forgiven. My gestalt is just that to get this passed, it is going to be a bit more nuanced than fixed-amount forgiveness.
Updating because recent backlash against congressional republicans will possibly give Biden pause

Given the complexity of this issue, I don't see how it is possible. That said, this may represent a last gasp for the Democrats before the midterms. Could be a play with the recent news on Roe v. Wade.
too much money at stake

While the math on forgiving $10K of principal for ~10M borrowers could be a sum that's really not at all hard to fund, the policy itself will certainly animate both sides. I will need to circle back in a few weeks after reading more. For now, I'll give it a high probability as a main gold star that Dems will flash coming up to Nov 8th.

This would cost $100 billion at a time of monetary tightening. It's unlikely to get many additional votes at the midterms, as most voters who want loan forgiveness will already vote Democrat. I doubt a bill would pass both House and Senate to become law given the current composition of each, but an executive order remains possible. As the $100 billion is a small increase in the total US debt then it remains a possible bribe to a small proportion of the electorate.

I think it's more likely that Biden will continue to pause payments on student loans. Additionally, some point to the deferred student loan payments as already contributing to inflation. Effectively another stimulus payment, the effect of forgiving student loan debt at this moment in time could lead to increased inflation.
@Maltaman unless the democrats want to lose the midterms
1. The Democratic needs to shore up support for the mid-terms.

Biden's White House has indicated that they are strongly considering student loan forgiveness, and recent reports suggest that student loan forgiveness will extend to single filers with an income cutoff of anywhere between 125K and 150K, or joint filers with a cutoff anywhere between 250K -300K per year.
This is such a bad idea that it is almost certain to happen.

A group of NY Times reporters are claiming the Democrats lack the votes in the Senate to pass legislation, as of two days ago: https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/27/business/dealbook/bidens-student-loans.html. But the White House is signaling that President Biden will sign an executive order, apparently notwithstanding objections from some staffers on economic or legal grounds. https://www.politico.com/news/2022/04/28/biden-considering-canceling-some-student-debt-00028663 And there's a lot of talk about the electoral benefit of such a move for the Dems in the mid-terms.

Midterm elections are coming up and Biden’s agenda has been stalling in Congress. With the American people suffering from the rise in inflation and the President’s dropping polling numbers, the President will have to take decisive action to rally his party and potential voters.
